content: Good overall basic scientific calculator but still missing a few general functions for statistics

Try cos (pi). Surprised it wasn't -1? I was too, and it makes me worry that the algorithms used for trigonometric solves in this don't adequately account for all the edge cases. It's one thing if Flappy Bird has round off errors, but a calculator shouldn't. Please look into the edge cases of all your functions a bit deeper. There's a lot of literature out there on catching them. Also check out test based development if you haven't already. A good unit test would have caught this.
replyContent: Hi. Please read the built-in help, RealCalc is an "immediate mode" calculator where you enter the value and then the function, e.g. œÄ then cos. Also make sure you are in radians, by using the DRG key. Thanks.

What can I say, I've really grown to love this app! I dislike the modern crop of calculators that make you input expressions as they're written on paper - e.g. "sin 30" or "log 10" simply because that's not what I got used to growing up. I'm far more used to banging in "30", then hitting "sin" to evaluate the expression; so I'm a lot more comfortable with RealCalc's default behaviour. I'm also familiar with RPN, so the inclusion of an RPN mode in this app is even more reassuring.  I haven't found a need to upgrade, but I'm seriously considering it simply to support the developer. But one point I'd like to make others aware of is this: Landscape support's supposed to be disabled in the free version. True enough, simply rotating the phone doesn't work; however, installing a third party app that 'forces' landscape mode (like AdaptiveLock) circumvents this, so Landscape mode becomes available.  One quibble. The mod function returns erroneous values for very large figures. E.g 3^70 (mod 71) should be 1, but the app gives 45. Clearly, round-off error is affecting it. Pls consider disabling such large inputs rather than giving wrong results. Other than that, keep it up!
